General overview

Node size is number of rows in a given table, edge size is number of overlapping PROG_ID values between 2 tables.

Osalejad / the people and roles dataset (n=342239)

Number of issues:

  • unicode letters (umlauts etc) are broken at the encoding level; I suspect this has gone through multiple broken re-encodings, as the entities they end up in are not typical UTF->ANSI errors, and are mixed with unicode-looking control chars
  • Some columns contain multiple entires in one cell, like REF_OSALUST, which lists all role types for a given actor or participant in a show (could be split apart if delimiting is systematic), or OSALEJA (participant) which can have longer descriptions like videoinsertide autorid Olavi Pihlam?gi ja Marek Inno. The longest such description is this: Lti NSV Kutsehariduse Kultuurimaja akad. Koor "Daile". Dir. Gido Kokor. Orelil Peteris Sipolnieks. OSALEJA field sometimes has last name only, sometimes its band names, sometimes first name is abbreviated to initials only.
  • There are empty cells - some make sense, if a show is not in a series then series is empty; but the role type is also sometimes empty.
  • 10475 missing IDs in INDEKS (cooccurs with NA in SERIES_ID not always; but PROG_ID always present)
  • sometimes the role and role type are in the PEALKIRI (title) field (e.g.Saatejuht Margus Saar)
  • sometimes (14726 times) OSALEJA is just ETV

Gender distributions over time in the most common roles

Uses a list of 5000 first names, focused on Estonian, Russian and Finnish, classfied as either male or female. This is matched against the first string in OSALEJA (delimited by space or hyphen - detection will rely on the first compnonent of multi-part names), preceded by a regex filter to get rid of most common cases of non-person-names (numbers, punctuation, >1 uppercase letters, mentions of film, tv, radio, music, band names, countries). Rows where the role type is one of Filmiahiiv, Tootja, Levitaja, iguste omanik are also ignored. OSALEJA is required to be between 2-50 characters, the inferred first name 2-11 (this seems to throw out a bunch of band and choir names, while keeping longer names like Christopher).

This filtering leaves 10,408 cases out of the original 342,239. The previously top frequent operaator category is reduced from 40k to 1231 (i.e.the names there are either initials, list multiple people, or no people at all), nitleja 36k->2038. Of those, the vast majority of names can be gendered simply by matching against the list (only 24 cases, 13 unique strings, are ambigous). Otherwise, the gender classifier could also use a bit of machine learning (e.g.string distance with k nearest neighbours) to classify unmatched names, but no need here really. This approach is, still, approximate, as some names might not be gender-specific, and this simple binary approach may misgender some people, including those who identify as nonbinary or trans. It is assumed though that this error margin would be reasonably low. It is also not impossible that less important roles are referred to using just initials, which means theyd be filtered out here; if the importance correlates with gender in some time periods, then this might also bias the results.

This graph above displays the most frequent role categories in the entire database (which has identifiable first names as the first element in the OSALEJA field), but it could also be done over time (for categories that have enough identifiable names). The number of available datapoints could potentially be increased by making the name detection in the OSALEJA field more comprehensive (where multiple names are mentioned; still doesnt help if just initials).

(All the) categories in REF_TOODANGU_LIIK and REF_EETRI_TUUP:

The ident category is explained in the accompaning documents, but it seems short (seconds to few minutes) clips containing titles such as ETV2 Tiiter Kurg Laste, ID ETV2 punkar, ID Hirivad stseenid, TIITER hetke prast Sgis Pehme, Kava HOMME (kevad) - so mostly short intermittent messages.

Saade (tv show, n=452675) and its type categories over time

By number of tv shows (regardless of duration)

By actual hours on air

Issue: 13372 have no duration entry; mostly before 2000 Those which do are displayed above, to give an idea how much time is allocated to different show types.

The plot below gives an overview of median saade duration over the years (a few outliers at very high values are omitted from this plot). The red line displays the percentage of saade/show entires which have a valid non-empty duration field. Since ~2000 theres fairly clear clusters of shows: most are ~25min, theres a smaller cluster at ~10min, and a smaller one at ~50min. The first plot is build on all the data (i.e.for series, every episode counts separately).

This zooms in on the last 20y, and series are are collapsed to one datapoint per year. The median is not necessarily informative, as there are 2-3 duration groups in there:

Durations of all REF_EETRI_TUUP categories

This also zooms in on the last 20 years. Some on-air duration values are likely messy, e.g.some shows that supposedly last 24h straight. Most REF_EETRI_TUUP=online (e.g.ERR uudised) have lengths of 3-5h, not sure what this means.

PROG (programme; n=300717)

EETRIAJAD seems like a smaller subset of the PROG table but with airing times: theres 47985 PROG_IDs and 3307 SERIES_IDs which dont occur in the EETRIAJAD table (but not vice versa). PROG only has ESMAEETER date (first airing, but 45986 missing values) and duration. Most entries with a first air date also have an entry in EETRIAJAD (which make sense). It does have more granular genre information and synopses (although for 67% synopsis/description fields are empty). Some rows are almost entirely empty (e.g.PROG_ID=10008133744: Uudistaja 7 saade 2. hange 05.05.2003, and thats it, doesnt belong to any series, has no more info).

SUNOPSIS and KIRJELDUS have short texts (median 200 and 500 characters). The longest kirjeldus is 35260 chars, the longest synopsis is 4000. Example synopis: Estonia Teatri laevareisi kolmas peatuskoht oli Oslo, kus esineti galakontserdiga. Viimases saates tehakse kokkuvtteid ooperireisist, kuulete estoonlaste muljeid ja arvamusi. Saatejuht Ruth Alakla". Some kirjeldus entries in English. Some have the same text in both fields (but noticed kirjeldus can have broken letters), some have only one field, 17243 have both, 202525 have neither. Example: SUNOPSIS=meelelahutuslik-petuslik lastesaade, KIRJELDUS= Koos Milo, Bella, Fizzi ja Jakeiga on vahva laule laulda ning maailma avastada, Maxil vi Judyl on aga varuks mni jutt ja meisterdamise idee. Tlkis Anti Reinthal.

SISUKIRJELDUS (content descriptions; n=212710)

  • No SERIES_ID columns
  • but PROG_ID duplicates unlike in the others; seems to describe multiple parts of the same show, but sometimes theres start time but no end time entry, and the start time entry can be 10 hours, e.g.11:35:51:00.
  • There are 293049 PROG_IDs and 280547 INDEKSs in PROG which do not occur in SISUKIRJELDUS, but all IDs in SISUKIRJELDUS are represented in PROG (and almost all, except for 431, occur in EETRIAJAD).
  • But its not only old ones missing, e.g.the earliest show with a SISUKIRJELDUS has an EETRIAEG air time entry of 1965-07-12. The missing ones are not immediately obvious (both oma and hange types, both Estonian and foreign, various genres, lengths, EETRI_TUUP types).

The median descriptions are 40 characters long. Dont seem to overlap with SUNOPSIS in PROG but might.

Topic modelling, combining all the text fields available

  • Concatenating here all the (non-technical) keyword fields (genre, audience, etc) and content fields (synopsis fields from PROG and content descriptions from SISUKIRJELDUS) + lemmatizing the longer/non-keyword text fields (keywords are kept as they are and prefixed with REF_).
  • Since the concatenation can potentially produce very uneven document lengths/number of terms per entry, I log-transformed all the frequencies of the terms coming from the free-text fields (keywords occur once per entry by definition even after concatenating series). Still, a long description can give more weight to the description terms than the metadata keywords. This would need further work.
  • Stopwords (conjunctions, numbers, adverbs etc) are removed.
  • This is based on the entire corpus, to get the most data to inform the topic model, but the analysis over time will be only on the saade category, as others are very small and/or seem to follow different logic (particularly online).
  • Topic model is LDA with k=9, alpha=0.05, beta = 0.01. Using low number of topics here to facilitate diachronic comparison.
  • One way or another its pretty much a sparse short-text modelling task, as some entries have very little descriptive content/metadata. To amend that a bit, I concatenated series (entries with a non-empty SERIES_ID field) into single entries (preserving/concatenating all their descriptions; but only one non-empty keyword in the keyword fields). This also solves some of the gaps in the data (some serie parts may have keywords or content, others not; making sure here to summarize using non-empty fields).
  • This leaves 17k entries of saade that have aired since 2000.
  • Another issue is mixed languages, some descriptive fields have English in them, which messes with the lemmatization and downstream topic distributions (I included English stopword removal to reduce their effect a bit).

Exploring topics

The topic model viewed through the lens of top 10 topic words; each row is a topic. Keep in mind that in LDA each document is a mixture of all the topics (but these values can also be 0). E.g. Aktuaalne Kaamera is mostly a mixture of topic 3 (42%) and 6 (55%). Note that this topic model might not be optimal, as the parameterization is fairly arbitrary (could also be better with phrases concatenated, e.g.right now aktuaalne kaamera is treated as two words). But this approach is a way to get around the issue of the sporadic lack of metadata and descriptions - some fields are populated for some entries, some for others, the topic model attempts to find latent structure underneath.

This UMAP dimension reduction shows all the saade type entries, mapped by their topic composition; each dot is a one-off show or a film or a series, colored by its primary topic (areas of multiple colors hence indicate entries with mixed topics, monochrome areas are likely single-topic entries).

Topics over time

This sums the hours on air durations for each topic for each month 2000 onwards. Since each entry/document is a normalized distribution over all topics, getting minutes per topic is a simple matter of multiplying the distributions by the minutes on air (as recorded in EETRIAJAD) and summing those for each unit of time (here monhts). The plot below normalizes the topic minutes for each month to maintain comparability. But:

  • note that this only takes into account tv contents only in the saade category, which doesnt cover everything (for example sport seems like a separate thing; online seems different),
  • only those that actually have some descriptions (keywords or synopses; 159 of saade dont),
  • and have time/duration entries in EETRIAJAD (2461 of saade 2000 onwards dont).
  • Also excluding 26 entries where the duration is over 6h assuming its errors (dont know whats a reasonable limit though, maybe some shows are super long).
  • And again, bear in mind, its a first messy possibly non-optimal attempt.

The gray topic is English desctiptions, which seems to have been more of an issue in mid-2000s. Red is the big stable topic, containing hints at politics, analytics, but also some sports. The pink one that ballooned and then diminishes seems to be a metadata thing in description fields - the longer keyword list with a higher-specificity lambda parameter is lputiiter foto koostama tekst saatepea istuma laud katkend kaadritagune raivo panoraam lembit jaanus lputiitrid kaader algustiiter sulev vli aare ain sirje enn merle peep erki, so a lot of names and techninal sounding terms. May be a topic, may be an issue of fields that should be in participant fields having been entered in content description or synopsis fields; would require further insight. The increase of the orange topic seems to be an increase of family oriented content like lasteekraan, prillitoos, leiutaja (Lotte?), but also Downton Abbey. The brown one is a bit of a mess of sports, Hercule Poirot and documentaries (so the k is apparently suboptimal), therefore a bit hard to interpret without diving into the descriptions.

Sidenote: noticed something odd: the distribution of the number of entries per month looks pretty unnatural (the low end is mostly early 2000s, but dont know why theres this multi-multimodal distribution).
